		<section>
			<section.front>
				<doc.title toc-guid="Id7206550682311ea83aee46e6decbb85">
					<head parent="doc.title">
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<label.name>§ </label.name>
						<label.designator>9:19.</label.designator>
						<headtext>Statements for purposes of medical diagnosis or treatment</headtext>
						<eos/>
						<eop/>
					</head>
				</doc.title>
			</section.front>
			<section.body>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>
						<cite.query w-src-number="0287017178" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USFRER803" w-pub-number="1000607" ID="I05454a5074d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Federal Rule of Evidence 803(4)</cite.query>
						<?page no="310"?> excludes from the hearsay rule any declarations of physical condition made for the purpose of medical diagnosis or treatment. <eos/>
						<bos/>This rule is identical to Georgia&apos;s former O.C.G.A. § 24-3-4 (now <cite.query w-src-number="0287017178" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-8-803" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I05454a5174d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-8-803(4)</cite.query>).<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Under <cite.query w-src-number="0287017178" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-8-803" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I0545987074d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-8-803(4)</cite.query>, <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“[s]tatements made for purposes of medical diagnosis or treatment and describing medical history, or past or present symptoms, pain, or sensations, or the inception or general character of the cause or external source thereof insofar as reasonably pertinent to diagnosis or treatment”<end.quote refid="QT_0001"/> shall not be excluded by the hearsay rule.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>The previous version of this statute was applied in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017178" w-serial-number="1978110009" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I054634b274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>Banks v. State</ital>
						</cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="I7a1f622074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>] to permit a nurse to testify about a child&apos;s emergency room statement of what had happened to her because the statements were pertinent to the child&apos;s diagnosis and treatment.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>The history that a patient gives to a psychologist, nurse, pediatrician, licensed professional counselor, or emergency room physician during examination or treatment has been held admissible under this exception to the hearsay rule.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7a1f622174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>] However, this exception relates only to patient statements and does not permit the admission of medical opinion included in a hospital record.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7a1f622274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>The exception has been applied only to statements that are pertinent to the “diagnosis or treatment” of the patient. <eos/>
						<bos/>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017178" w-serial-number="1979127287" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I0548308274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>Johnson v. State</ital>
						</cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I7a1f893074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>] the Georgia Court of Appeals held that statements by an incest victim regarding previous acts of incest were not pertinent to diagnosis or treatment. <eos/>
						<bos/>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017178" w-serial-number="2043194334" w-seq-number="00016" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I0549690274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>State v. Almanza,</ital>
						</cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="I7a1f893174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">5</footnote.reference>] the Court of Appeals excluded statements by the mother made to the attending physicians as to the identification of the defendant during her daughter&apos;s physical examination; however, <cite.query w-src-number="0287017178" w-serial-number="2043194334" w-seq-number="00018" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I054c011274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>Almanza</ital>
						</cite.query> was overruled by the Georgia Supreme Court,[<footnote.reference refid="I7a1f893274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">6</footnote.reference>] which held that identification of a defendant by a child declarant during an examination by a physician may be admissible under the test set out by the Eighth Circuit in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017178" w-serial-number="1985160087" w-seq-number="00020" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000350" ID="I054cc46174d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>U.S. v. Renville</ital>
						</cite.query>.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7a1f893374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">7</footnote.reference>
						<?page no="311"?>] Thus, to be allowed under <cite.query w-src-number="0287017178" w-seq-number="00022" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-8-803" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I054d60a074d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-8-803(4)</cite.query>, the trial court must determine (1) that the declarant&apos;s motive in making the statement is consistent with the purposes of promoting diagnosis or treatment, and (2) that the content of the statement was reasonably relied on by a physician in treatment or diagnosis. <eos/>
						<bos/>This two-step test ensures that the hearsay statement has a sufficient guarantee of trustworthiness.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Similarly, in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017178" w-serial-number="1982107001" w-seq-number="00023" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I054dd5d274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>Lewis v. State</ital>
						</cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I7a1fb04074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">8</footnote.reference>] the court held that remarks identifying the defendant were not admissible because the statements must be made by or on behalf of a patient seeking medical aid. <eos/>
						<bos/>Thus, in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017178" w-serial-number="1991113539" w-seq-number="00026" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I054e992274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>Pirkle v. Hawley</ital>
						</cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I7a1fb04174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">9</footnote.reference>] the court held admissible under former O.C.G.A. § 24-3-4[<footnote.reference refid="I7a1fb04274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">10</footnote.reference>] statements that the plaintiff had stopped breathing, which were made to a police officer at the scene of a traffic accident. <eos/>
						<bos/>Also, an emergency medical technicians&apos; testimony regarding defendants&apos; admitted drug use on the night before the traffic accident was admissible as pertinent in the provision of emergency medical treatment.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7a1fb04374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">11</footnote.reference>] The Supreme Court in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017178" w-serial-number="2036450456" w-seq-number="00029" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I054ff8b274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>Neuman v. State,</ital>
						</cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="I7a1fb04474d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">12</footnote.reference>] opined that statements in a psychotherapist&apos;s notes, made during individual counseling sessions with the defendant&apos;s wife, which the psychotherapist used for medical diagnosis or treatment were not admissible under former O.C.G.A. § 24-3-4, but rather were privileged communications between the psychotherapist and the defendant&apos;s wife.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
			</section.body>
		</section>
